New Order of the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the Policy Planning Staff at the US Department of State, explains his "Roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq – and what the Iraqi people, with the help of the Americans, can now build up above all – will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could bring about reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take time before far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the Middle East have been grasped.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security policy, economic, and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning of the Americans and the entire world and thanks to the rapid, concentrated, and targeted intervention of the coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less than expected.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but the announced massive crisis fortunately never occurred.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. The supply of food, water, and medicine is sufficient in most cases or at least improving.
The American government has made approximately 600 million dollars available through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
Furthermore, we must restore the order in Iraq.
Safety is the indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without safety, the people cannot rebuild their country, cannot return to work or schools.
After the fall of Saddam, there was a wave of plundering, lawlessness, and settling of scores.
Now, it is the top priority to put an end to this violence.
In addition, it must be the task of international troops to ensure and eliminate all mass destruction weapons, to prevent and ensure that the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts does not occur, and that none of Iraq's neighbors further worsen the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis to rebuild their police and military structures, so that they can take care of their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be considered more precisely as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
Unlike many other post-war scenarios, Iraq has a lot of raw materials to process.
The US is providing more than 2 billion dollars in support for the initial reconstruction efforts.
The oil production is being raised to a better level.
Among the long-term challenges are an increase in oil production and the repayment of the enormous debts of Iraq.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome in this case.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographical, and political cleavages in Iraqi society, the help with the political renewal of Iraq is probably the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq, where the law is respected and the government comes into being democratically - is not a castle in the air, especially because Iraq has an educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue the course set and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are implemented.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be used.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly an external policy issue that has occupied and polarized public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian question.
About almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratically governed Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU and the United Nations, the US developed a roadmap that brings us closer to this goal step by step.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to initiate this process and take steps to improve the situation, in order to take up more far-reaching topics at the negotiating table afterwards.
Ultimately, it cannot be that terrorists make the peace process futile for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically also the solution to all the problems of the Middle East.
Clear and evident are the challenges which the Iran poses to us. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and is supporting terrorism.
Such behavior spurns the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues in this way, it will have consequences.
However, if one turns away from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the US is ready to take up good relations with this country again.
Just as the US is ready to take up a relationship with Syria if one there undertakes substantial policy changes.
A more general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
America has for too long tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to intervene in the matter of representative government.
We have painfully experienced that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the US, the West and the world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, that was initiated by Foreign Minister Colin Powell in December 2002.
Closed economic systems are also a threat.
As emerges from the previous year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development State of the Arab Countries), the Arab countries of the Middle East have fallen far behind in the areas of personal freedom, women's rights, and economic and social development compared to other regions.
For too long, these countries have had to watch as the economic boom went by without them.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If one were to realize his recently proposed suggestion of a free trade zone between the US and the Middle East within a decade, that would be a sound basis for such development.
